<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06051336 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06051336 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  HOMELESS; FAMILY; CHARITY; ORGANIZATION; BEGIN  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A South San Jose couple are launching an ambitious project to aid a sometimesforgotten segment of the American population.;    Ken and Vicky De Hart havefounded a non-profit organization called Home for the Homeless and are hopingto raise enough money through weekly bingo games, corporate donations andprivate and federal grants to fulfill a short-term goal of providing temporaryhousing for homeless families.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Extra 4  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  COUPLE AID S.J. FAMILIESHOMELESS PROJECT SEEKS DONATIONS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Also ran in EX2/6  </MEMO><TEXT>     They have also placed clear plastic canisters with the organization's nameprinted on them in stores around San Jose, Los Gatos, Campbell and Sunnyvaleseeking donations from the public.;    &quot;As soon as we have a steady income,we'll try to contract homes and apart ments for three months. Or if there arefamilies that need help with rents, we'll try to do that,&quot; co-founder Ken DeHart said.;    The De Harts, who began the Home for the Homeless program ayear and a half ago, are hoping to eventually purchase a ranch where they canprovide a permanent residence for homeless and abused children.;    Ken DeHart, 53, a native of Indiana who has lived in the Bay Area for 15 years,decided to get involved with helping the homeless because of his ownbackground.;    One of 10 children, he began working at age 9 to support hisbrothers and sisters after his parents divorced.;    The Home for the Homelessproject was something he had wanted to do for a number of years, but onlyrecently took time out to sit down and begin organizing it.;    &quot;My kids areall grown and I don't want to spend the rest of my life doing nothing,&quot; hesaid.;    De Hart, a former Realtor and self-employed businessman, said heplans to sell his half of a partnership in a deli and convenience store inSunnyvale so he can work with the project full-time.;    &quot;I'm not doing thisfor the money . . . I'm doing it because I want to,&quot; he said. De Hart addedthat most of the staff for the group is volunteer.;    He said he chose bingoas his chief means of fund-raising because it has proved highly successful forchurches and schools.;    &quot;About 40 to 50 percent of the charities used bingoas a means of fund-raising and are able to do pretty well,&quot; he said.;    TheDe Harts held their first bingo game last week at the SES Hall in Santa Clara.De Hart said he was cheered by the 245 people who attended.;    &quot;It wentpretty smoothly and we may have even shown a little profit,&quot; he said.;    Theyplan to hold the games every Tuesday, and are looking for volunteers to help.;   &quot;We'll be giving away a $250 cash prize each week and a color television,&quot;he said.;    De Hart said he plans to run his group differently from othershe's heard about.;    &quot;(In other groups) I found out that 80 to 90 percent ofthe money that's taken in goes to administrative costs and 10 percent goes tothe homeless,&quot; he said. &quot;Ours is not going to work that way. I want 80 to 90percent to go back to the homeless.&quot;; IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; The bingo gameswill be held every Tuesday at the SES Hall, Lafayette and Lewis Streets nearEl Camino Real in Santa Clara. The doors open at 4:30 p.m. and games willbegin at 6:30. If you wish to volunteer or want more information about Homefor the Homeless, call (408) 281-2300.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  LORI ARATANI, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910220  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  589  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday February 20, 199100051336,S